A proposed strontium titanate quantum sensor (transducer) for detecting
coherent acoustic phonons with a superconducting qubit. The qubit-phonon coupling is based on
the high sensitivity of superconducting strontium titanate to local lattice deformations as it is
tuned towards the polar phase transition. An acoustic phonon could be delivered to the strontium
titanate qubit which then changes its impedance as the Josephson energy of the strained system
is higher than the unstrained system.

Further experimental efforts motivated by our results can focus on direct phonon measurement
and manipulation techniques; combined with probes like electronic transport, scanning SQUID imaging
), phonon manipulation could bring to life new ideas such as probing
strain responses, potentially leading to even higher critical temperatures not accessible
with the static strains used in this work.
The almost 0.8 K onset critical temperature reported here makes strained superconducting
strontium titanate comparable to superconducting aluminum. Similar to aluminum, strontium titanate
could be used in superconducting qubits. Hybrid structures of doped and undoped strontium titanate may
